{{Refimprove|date=August 2007}} '''Attachment of earnings''' is a [[legal process]] in [[civil litigation]] by which a [[defendant]]'s wages or other earnings are taken to pay for a [[debt]]. This collections process is used in the [[common law]] system, especially [[U.K.|Britain]] and the [[United States]], but in other legal regimes as well.<ref>Some cites are needed for other countries, esp. India, Africa</ref>
''[[Ballentine's Law Dictionary]]'' notes that this process is not literal, whereby a "person's property is figuratively brought into the court."<ref>Ballentine's Law Dictionary, at p. 38</ref>
The [[earnings]] seized may be [[wages]], certain benefits, or [[sales]] commissions. {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}
A [[sheriff]], [[constable]], or [[Marshal#Law enforcement|marshall]] enforces the court order. {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}
==United Kingdom== In [[England]], an attachment of earning order can stop money being paid to a defendant.<ref>[http://www.hmcourts-service.gov.uk/infoabout/enforcement/ae/index.htm See the British government web site regarding this]</ref>
Under English law, a self-employed, unemployed, or member of the armed forces can '''not''' have an attachment against them.
In England, the District Council can attach earnings.<ref>[http://www.eden.gov.uk/main.asp?page=369 See the Eden Council web page] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927101929/http://www.eden.gov.uk/main.asp?page=369 |date=September 27, 2007 }}</ref> This may be by a physical removal of the money or other personal property. However, more commonly, the officer merely contacts the [[bank]], [[landlord]], [[employer]], [[trustee]], [[bailment|bailee]] or other person holding the property, with a [[certified copy]] of the order, for them to hand over the debtor's property for attachment; this is especially true with intangible personal property and [[real property]]. {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}
==United States== At present four U.S. states — North Carolina, Pennsylvania, South Carolina and Texas — do not allow wage garnishment at all except for debts related to taxes, child support, federally guaranteed student loans, and court-ordered fines or restitution for a crime the debtor committed. Several other states observe maximum thresholds that are lower than the 25 percent maximum provided by federal law. States may also prohibit garnishment altogether in certain circumstances. For example, in Florida the wages of a person who provides more than half the support for a child or other dependent are exempt from garnishment altogether (though this exemption is subject to waiver).
In New York, a limit of 10 percent of gross earnings may be taken for ordinary debts.<ref>See, e.g., N.Y. CPLR section 5205; also, see 11 U.S.C.A. Chapter 7.</ref> However, 15 percent may be taken for student loans, {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}} and up to 40 percent for [[child support]] arrears,<ref>N.Y. CPLR sections 5241, 5241</ref> or even higher. {{Citation needed|date=August 2007}}
In many [[United States|American]] jurisdictions, attachment of earnings is treated the same as, or is just called, [[garnishment]]. This is when either earnings, and/or [[property]] may be taken by the court.
